          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">Tajikistan and Taliban: a complex relationship</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/tajikistan-taliban-relations-regional-stability-cross-border-trade.png" alt="Emomali Rahmon's government has publicly rejected the Taliban and offered support to its opponents, including hosting Afghan exiles and criticizing Taliban measures" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Emomali Rahmon's government has publicly rejected the Taliban and offered support to its opponents, including hosting Afghan exiles and criticizing Taliban measures. Credits: Press Service of President of Tajikistan/REUTERS
          </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Tajikistan and Taliban-led Afghanistan have a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-may-25-analysis-h1-1-complicated-and-contradictory-relationship?source=website" target="_blank">complicated and contradictory relationship</a>. While Tajikistan publicly rejects the Taliban, labeling them an extremist group and supporting their opponents, economic realities are pushing both sides toward limited engagement.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Ties such as electricity exports and the reopening of border markets have created a level of practical cooperation. Despite their differences, the Taliban have issued positive statements about relations with Tajikistan and have hosted Tajik delegations.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          However, tensions remain. The Taliban continue to shelter the Tajik militant group Jamaat Ansarullah and have opened channels with political opponents of Tajik President Emomali Rahmom, including exiled leader Sharofiddin Gadoev. Gadoevâ€™s recent visit to Kabul and his public criticism of Rahmon on Afghan media likely occurred with Taliban approval.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          This signals that the Taliban are keeping their options open and looking to expand their influence in the region. Although full normalization of ties is unlikely due to deep-rooted mistrust dating back to Tajikistanâ€™s civil war, analysts believe low-level cooperation will continue, especially as trade grows and visa rules are eased.
            </p>
          </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
