          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">The Philippines</h2>
        </mj-text>
          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/philippines-named-after-king-philip-ii-spanish-colonization.png" alt="The Philippines takes its name from Philip II, king of Spain, who ruled the islands during the Spanish colonization of the islands in the 16th century." href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          The Philippines takes its name from Philip II, king of Spain, who ruled the islands during the Spanish colonization in the 16th century. 
          </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-may-25-ktt-h1-4-philippines?source=website" target="_blank">Philippines</a> is a Southeast Asia archipelago with over 7,000 islands. It is famous for its cultural diversity, tropical landscapes, and strategic Pacific location. With a population exceeding 110Mn, the country also has a vast diaspora spread across the globe.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The Philippines has long held strategic geopolitical importance due to its location in the western Pacific, at the crossroads of major sea lanes linking East and Southeast Asia. Historically, it was colonized by Spain and later the United States, shaping its political and military ties.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         During World War II, it was a key battleground in the Pacific theater. In the Cold War, it hosted major US military bases, serving as a counterbalance to Soviet and Chinese influence in Asia.
            </p>
          </mj-text>
